07427nam a22009135i 9781787440333DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20172017xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781787440333  a(DE-B1597)674425  a(OCoLC)1036778919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aD116b.U57 2017eb 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a940.107222300aUniversal Chronicles in the High Middle Ages /ced. by Michele Campopiano, Henry Bainton.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2017] 1bYork Medieval Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b16 b/w, 1 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWriting History in the Middle Ages ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: New Perspectives on Universal Chronicles in the High Middle Ages -- t1 The First Islamic Chronicle: The Chronicle Of Khalīfa B. Khayyāṭ (d. AD 854) -- t2 Universal Historiography as Process? Shaping Monastic Memories in the Eleventh-Century Chronicle Of Saint-Vaast -- t3 Writing Universal History in Eleventh-Century England: Cotton Tiberius B. i, German Imperial History-writing and Vernacular Lay Literacy -- t4 Political Didacticism in the Twelfth Century: the Middle-High German Kaiserchronik -- t5 Cosmology, Theology of History and Ideology in Godfrey of Viterbo’s Pantheon -- t6 Écrire l’histoire universelle à la cour de Konrad IV de Hohenstaufen : la Weltchronik de Rudolf von Ems (milieu du XIIIe siècle) -- t7 Écrire la première histoire universelle en français: l’Histoire ancienne jusqu’à César de Wauchier de Denain et l’adaptation du modèle latin de l’histoire universelle à un public de laïcs -- t8 How Unusual was Matthew Paris? The Writing of Universal History in Angevin England -- t9 The Pillars of Hercules: The Estoria De Espanna (Escorial, Y.I.2) as Universal Chronicle -- t10 La Vie d’Alexandre dans la Chronique dite de Baudouin d’Avesnes -- t11 Universal Histories and their Geographies: Navigating the Maps and Texts of Higden’s Polychronicon -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew perspectives on and interpretations of the popular medieval genre of the universal chronicle.Found in pre-modern cultures of every era and across the world, from the ancient Near East to medieval Latin Christendom, the universal chronicle is simultaneously one of the most ubiquitous pre-modern cultural forms and one of the most overlooked. Universal chronicles narrate the history of the whole world from the time of its creation up to the then present day, treating the world's affairs as though they were part of a single organic reality, and uniting various strands of history into a unifed, coherent story. They reveal a great deal about how the societies that produced them understood their world and how historical narrative itself can work to produce that understanding.The essays here offer new perspectives on the genre, from a number of different disciplines, demonstrating their vitality, flexibility and cultural importance, They reveal them to be deeply political texts, which allowed history-writers and their audiences to locate themselves in space, time and in the created universe. Several chapters address the manuscript context, looking at the innovative techniques of compilation, structure and layout that placed them at the cutting edge of medieval book technology. Others analyse the background of universal chronicles, and identify their circulation amongst different social groups; there are also investigations into their literary discourse, patronage, authorship and diffusion. Michele Campopiano is Senior Lecturer in Medieval Latin Literature at the University of York; Henry Bainton is Lecturer in High Medieval Literature at the University of York. Contributors:Tobias Andersson, Michele Campopiano, Cornelia Dreer, Catherine Gaullier-Bougassas, Elena Koroleva, Keith Lilley, Andrew Marsham, Rosa M. Rodriguez Porto, Christophe Thierry, Elizabeth M. Tyler, Steven Vanderputten, Bjorn Weiler, Claudia Wittig.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aHistoriographyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aMiddle AgesxHistoriography. 0aWorld historyvEarly works to 1800. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEnglish.  aauthorship.  aculture.  afolore.  agenre.  aliterary analysis.  aliterature.  amanuscript.  amedieval.  amiddle ages.  anarrative.  aoral history.  atext.  auniversal chronicle.  awriting.1 aAndersson, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBainton, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampopiano, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampopiano, Michele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDreer, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaullier-Bougassas, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoroleva, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLilley, Keith D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsham, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodríguez Porto, Rosa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThierry, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTyler, Elizabeth M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVanderputten, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiler